         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
<ab><lb n="1"/>      <space quantity="1" unit="character"/>  <persName type="emperor"><name nymRef="#Ἁδριανός">Ἁδριανῷ  </name><space quantity="1" unit="character"/>  
   <lb n="2"/>    <space quantity="2" unit="character"/> <addName nymRef="Σωτήρ">Σωτῆρι</addName> <space quantity="1" unit="character"/>  
   <lb n="3"/>    <space quantity="3" unit="character"/>    <persName ref="#zeus" type="divine"><name nymRef="#Ζεύς">Διὶ</name> <space quantity="3" unit="character"/>
      <lb n="4"/>    <supplied reason="lost"><space quantity="1" unit="character"/></supplied>    <addName nymRef="Ὀλύμπιος"><supplied reason="lost">Ὀ</supplied>λυμπίῳ</addName></persName></persName>  <space quantity="1" unit="character"/><lb n="4a"/><space quantity="8" unit="character"/></ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To Hadrian the Saviour Zeus Olympios.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of several small 'altars' dedicated to Hadrian:  <ref type="inscription" n="1277" target="iAph090119"/> (=81.98), <seg cert="low">
                  <ref type="inscription" n="1266" target="iAph080256"/> (=70.254)</seg>
            </p>
            <p>The title Zeus Olympios is thought to follow from the dedication of the Olympieion at Athens in autumn 129.</p>
            <p>The absence of a dedicator's name is unexpected.</p>
         </div>
